text.tspan: a colour a second
Inspired by OK Go – Of the Blue Colour of the Sky album cover visualizations, I used a radial graph to compare both
episodes for my first graph, Colours Timeline. Humans are naturally drawn to circles, making radial graphs
aesthetically pleasing in general yet limiting in terms of their ability to tell accurate information, as they make specific
data points harder to read. However, in my case and given the number of data points I am dealing with —2374 colour
stripes from the first episode and 2224 from the finale— a radial graph allows me to render them in a circler form that
simplifies the data points. It also saves me the need to sacrifice some of the data while keeping the two data sets
easily comparable. Labels are placed on the graph, directly eliminating the need for a legend, and a light background
was used to make the -mostly dark- colours pop.
Initially, I wanted to go with two timeline-based stacked bar charts similar to CATO Visual Color Script for the Colours
timeline, where I would create one for each episode and place them next to each other. However, during the very
lengthy process of extracting and grouping colours to do so, I paused for a second as I was trying to group colours to
appreciate the look of all the colour lines and the amount of info each colour stripe holds, which would be lost if I
succeed in grouping colours.
who's most talkative?
For my second visualization, I used a Voronoi Treemap to compare characters' lines and mentions. Similar to regular
Treemaps, Voronoi Treemap allows me to display hierarchically structured data compactly and use size as another
data layer and a comparison factor. Voronoi Treemap has the additional benefit of its cells taking the shape of an
outline that makes the most sense to the data rather than the Treemap default rectangles.
This was a hard pick, as I spent over three hours finding the most ideal and exciting chart, and it wouldn't be more
suitable for one of my other visualizations as I wish to avoid using the same graph type twice. Out of all graphs
explored, Voronoi Treemaps proved to provide me with a visually exciting comparison of the different characters
across both episodes that is both compact and easy to read.
My Voronoi Treemap takes the outline of a hexagon in reference to Arcane's Hextech, the discovery that links all these
characters together and the core of the show's plot. Characters are limited to only those present or mentioned in both
the first and last episodes of the show for simplifications purposes. Masked images represent each character, while
colours differentiate the episodes reducing clutter and improving chart reading times, as characters' faces are more
memorable and easier to recognize than names. Legend is centred below the graph to align the reading hierarchy —
First, explore the chart. Then scan the legend— with natural eye movement from top to bottom, whereas placing it at
the top makes it go unnoticed.
from powder to jinx
To my surprise, Spline Graph ended up being my graph of choice for visualizing the Powder to Jinx transformation. A
spline chart is a type of line chart that uses curves rather than straight lines. Like line charts, they are designed to
emphasize trends over a time series (in this case, the different episodes) but more gradually.
Line charts, in general, are not on top of my list of the most interesting charts; however, when I was exploring my
different chart options, they ended up being the most suitable option for comparing the relationships between Jinx and
Powder with a count of their lines and mentions. It is simple, it makes the relationship crystal clear, and the curve
somehow ended, giving a reasonable estimate of how the episodes in between factor in the trend of Powder turning
into Jinx.
Design-wise, I used a dark background to make lines stand out, and because the graph's topic is part of the previous
page so I wanted to keep that continuously with the background.
